<H3> <TI>   Southern Cone Environmental Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Southern Cone Environmental Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1103182994 </F>
<F P=103> PY1103182994 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on environmental issues monitored through 10 March. 
  BRAZIL 
  At least five areas of the country, totalling more than 
115,000 square kilometers, are experiencing desertification. 
According to Sao Paulo University Professor Jose Bueno Conti, 
the most critical areas are in the northeastern part of the 
country. The largest area, which includes Bahia, Piaui, Ceara, 
Pernambuco, Alagoas, and Sergipe States, is nearly 100,000 
square kilometers, almost two and a half times the area of Rio 
de Janeiro. The desertification also affects the municipality of 
Alegrete, in the southern part of Rio Grande do Sul State, the 
municipality of Paranavai, Parana State, and Roraima State. (Rio 
de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 13 Feb 94 p 7) 
  Brazil and the African countries are vying for attention in 
the international convention on desertification that will be 
signed in Paris in June. This so-called convention of the poor 
alludes to those conventions on climate changes and biodiversity 
agreed on during the Rio 92 environmental conference. The 
convention on desertification involves international financial 
aid and technological support. (Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL 
in Portuguese 6 Mar 94 p 21) 

</TEXT>

