<H3> <TI>   U.S. Stand on Nuclear Issue at Hague Talks Creates Concern </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Stand on Nuclear Issue at Hague Talks Creates Concern </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0804105794 Tel Aviv MA'ARIV in Hebrew 8 Apr 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> TA0804105794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv MA'ARIV </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Hemi Shalev] </F>
  [Text] There is tension between Israel and the United 
States as a result of the United States' having supported Egypt 
yesterday in its demand that the handling of nuclear waste be 
put on the agenda of the multinational talks on environment 
issues being held in The Hague. 
  As a result of diplomatic contacts between Washington and 
Jerusalem and following a telephone conversation between Foreign 
Minister Shim'on Peres and U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher, the secretary agreed to modify the Egyptian demand 
and support a multinational discussion of issues relating only 
to regional legislation on handling nuclear waste. 
  Christopher accepted Israel's position that Egypt's charges 
that Israel is mishandling nuclear waste should be broached by 
the two countries on a bilateral level and not at the 
multinational talks. 
  The Egyptian demand is part of the very energetic campaign 
regarding Israel's nuclear ability which Egypt is waging at the 
multinational talks on armament issues as well. Two days ago, 
before The Hague talks started, the Egyptians warned they would 
boycott the talks if their demand to discuss nuclear waste is 
not accepted. They changed their mind only after the United 
States intervened. 
  Last night, Israeli sources expressed concern over the U.S. 
support -- partial though it may be -- for the Egyptian stand. 
  The sources said that ever since the new U.S. Administration 
came into power, there has been a constant threat of conflict 
between it and Israel in view of Washington's determined policy 
on nuclear nonproliferation. Because of the close U.S.-Israeli 
contacts, the issue has not come up yet. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

