<H3> <TI>     UN Security Council Statement on DPRK Inspections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Security Council Statement on DPRK Inspections </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Tokyo Backs UNSC Stand </H4>

<F P=102> OW0104032394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0258 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0104032394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 1 KYODO -- Japan on Friday [1 April] 
supported a United Nations call on North Korea to allow full 
international inspection of its nuclear facilities suspected of 
being used to develop nuclear weapons. 
  "The UN statement underlined what the international 
community 
wants North Korea to do to help resolve the issue of Pyongyang's 
suspected nuclear program through dialogue," Chief Cabinet 
Secretary Masayoshi Takemura told a news conference. 
  "We will support this statement," the top government 
spokesman said. 
  All 15 members of the UN Security Council, including China, 
a 
traditional ally of North Korea, agreed to issue the statement 
Thursday calling for Pyongyang to accept full inspections by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency. 

</TEXT>

