<H3> <TI>   Peru To Help Mexico Fight Terrorism </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peru To Help Mexico Fight Terrorism </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2803203694 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1531 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2803203694 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 27 Mar (EFE) -- The Peruvian media reported 
today that the Mexican Government has asked Peru to help their 
anti-terrorist struggle. 
  The Lima daily EXPRESO says that within the next few days 
two 
National Police Counterterrorism Directorate (Dincote) experts 
will travel to the Mexican capital with President Alberto 
Fujimori's authorization. 
  EXPRESO cites high-ranking police sources who state that the 
officers are Colonel Juan Gonzalez Sandoval and Lieutenant 
Colonel Alberto Sarmiento Gutierrez. 
  It adds that Gonzalez and Sarmiento will be in Mexico for at 
least 10 days. 
  Mexican officials want to learn the Peruvian way of facing a 
possible upsurge of the terrorist phenomenon following the 
Chiapas rebellion and the death of presidential candidate Luis 
Donaldo Colosio. 

</TEXT>

