<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TOT-94-014-L </AU>
JPRS 
Terrorism 

</HEADER>

<ABS>  FOUO </ABS>
<DATE1>   8 April 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> PERU </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Insurgent Activities Through 31 March </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Insurgent Activities Through 31 March </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY3103212194 </F>
<F P=103> PY3103212194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on insurgent activities in Peru compiled from Peruvian 
media monitored through 31 March. 
  Security forces from the Political-Military Command of the 
Fifth Security Sub-Zone arrested 18 alleged Shining Path 
``terrorists'' in Puno Department. Some of the main leaders 
under arrest are Luis Mamani Alvarez, ``Comrade Cleto;'' 
Leovigildo Efrain Jara Hualla, ``Comrade Carlos;'' Estanislao 
Flabio Mamani Gutierrez, ``Comrade Cesar;'' Serapio Aguilar 
Pari, ``Comrade Raul;'' Juan Pedro Quispe Mamani, ``Comrade 
Jorge;'' and Natividad Quispe Butron. (Lima EL COMERCIO in 
Spanish 19 Mar 94 p A12) 
  One soldier was killed and three civilians seriously wounded 
in a 17 March clash between a military patrol and more than 100 
Shining Path members who attacked the Puente Duran settlement, 
Huanuco Province, which is located 65 km south of Tingo Maria. A 
military spokesman said the subversives tried to take over the 
settlement to get food. (Lima LA REPUBLICA in Spanish 20 Mar 94 
p 19) 
  About 186 peasants who were recruited five months ago by 
Shining Path members and were staying in the ``Sello de Oro'' 
camp decided to surrender to the Army in Santa Rosa, Ayacucho 
Department. They are being held in the Pichari garrison in the 
Apurimac River valley about 220 km northeast of Ayacucho. (Lima 
EL COMERCIO in Spanish 24 Mar 94 p A14) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

