<H3> <TI>   BABIL: Sources Allege Basil Al-Asad Killed by Drug </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    BABIL: Sources Allege Basil Al-Asad Killed by Drug </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
`Gangsters' 

<F P=102>   JN3003120594 Baghdad BABIL in Arabic 26 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> JN3003120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad BABIL </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>
BFN 

  [Text] Watchers of the Syrian scene and arrivals from Syria 
report that Basil, President Hafiz al-Asad's eldest son, met his 
death at the hands of drug gangsters operating in Lebanon. 
  According to some reliable sources, Basil was killed in 
Lebanon, having received threats in connection with the hush 
money he had been receiving from hashish growers and smugglers. 
He had been suspected of planning to swindle the traffickers 
and control the market. 
  The sources indicate that the news of Basil's death, 
officially caused by an auto crash, was broken two days after 
its actual date. Neither was there any picture of the accident 
that could be shown on Syrian television. 
  Observers note that Lebanese factions, the Maronites in 
particular, were keen to send delegations to pay their last 
respects, lest any be suspected of involvement in his 
assassination and then bear the vengeance of Syrian intelligence 
services. 
  The observers are confident that the next few days will bear 
out their assessment. A tradition of the al-Nasiriyah sect 
calls for the deceased's face to be uncovered for a final 
glimpse, which was not observed in the case of Basil al-Asad. 

</TEXT>

