</HEADER>

<ABS>  FOUO </ABS>
<DATE1>   30 March 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> RUSSIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Officials Report Moscow Explosion `Ordinary Crime' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Interior Officials Report Moscow Explosion `Ordinary Crime' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3003183294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1755 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3003183294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 30 TASS--An explosion which occurred in 
the Osenny Boulevard in the vicinity of a new residence of the 
Russian president ``does not have a political colouring,'' 
ITAR-TASS was told at the Russian president's press service. 
``This is an ordinary crime,'' the press service said, relying 
on a conclusion made by competent interior officials. 
  At 12:30 p.m. Wednesday, an explosive device went off in a 
Zhiguli car parked in the yard of a house located in the Osenny 
Boulevard, 12, block 2. The explosion killed a driver of the 
``Oton'' trade company who lived there, and ``a criminal boss'' 
was injured. The criminal was hospitalized. Two more girls, 
aged 8 and 10, were injured. The explosion was presumably 
targeted at the ``criminal element'' interior officials said. 
  The incident occurred at a distance of one kilometer from a 
new city residence of the Russian president. Neither Boris 
Yeltsin, nor his family are living in the new house yet. 

</TEXT>

